{
  "article_id": "Hudson1978_52(4)",
  "paragraphs": [
    [
      {
        "text": "IN ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "A PREVIOUS ISSUE of THE MASTERKEY (",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Vol. 52",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": ", "
      },
      {
        "text": "No. 1",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "; January-March, 1978)",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": ", I reported the exciting discovery of some ethnographic notes among John P. Harrington's papers which pertained to ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the \"Lone Woman\" of San Nicolas Island",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ".",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": " These materials were found in Boxes 4 and 745 of his Chumash material culture and ritual notes, now housed in the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Smithsonian Institution",
        "entity_key": "mu_smithsonian",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ". Recently I came across some additional material on this interesting segment of California history in Box 747, which also pertains to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Chumash",
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " ethnography. The edited notes are provided below. As with the first series of notes on "
      },
      {
        "text": "this woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", the informant is "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando Librado",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ":"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "Captain Nidever",
        "entity_key": "gni",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "an Indian named Malquiares",
        "entity_key": "msh",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "1 found "
      },
      {
        "text": "a woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " on "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas Island",
        "entity_key": "sni",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " rolling silver2 in her hands to make abalorio.3 "
      },
      {
        "text": "Malquiares",
        "entity_key": "msh",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " spoke to her at Captain Nidever's request. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Malquiares",
        "entity_key": "msh",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " told "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " that when they encountered "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", she sang the following song:4"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "tokitoki\nyamymna\ntokitoki\nweleleshkima\nyaamymina\nweleleshkima\nyaamymina\ntokitoki"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "The woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " sang these words. After hearing them "
      },
      {
        "text": "Malquiares",
        "entity_key": "msh",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " could sing them, and they later became deeply impressed on Fernando's memory. Once, when "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " met "
      },
      {
        "text": "Aravio",
        "entity_key": "atal",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ",5 a very aged Indian from "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Ines",
        "entity_key": "ci_sy",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " recited these words to him, and at once "
      },
      {
        "text": "Aravio",
        "entity_key": "atal",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " translated the song for "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". The words meant: \"I leave contented, because I see the day when I want to get out of "
      },
      {
        "text": "this island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ".\""
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "When discovered the woman's only clothing consisted of a skirt made of feathers and an apron. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Jacob [George] Nidever",
        "entity_key": "gni",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " and his people were otter hunters. They made "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " a dress out of their trousers. It was a month that they stayed on "
      },
      {
        "text": "the island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " before they found "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". After they found her, she would not eat their food, but she did stay around their camp. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Mr. L. A. M. Ortega",
        "entity_key": "lor",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "6 says that he has heard that after "
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " was removed to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", she was a great hand at eating tallow. "
      },
      {
        "text": "The woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " was taken to "
      },
      {
        "text": "the house",
        "entity_key": "nideverhouse",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " of "
      },
      {
        "text": "Jacob Nidever's folks",
        "entity_keys": [
          "gni",
          "sni"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " in "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", an adobe situated close to where the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Southern Pacific Freight Station",
        "entity_key": "spacstation",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " now stands.7 When "
      },
      {
        "text": "the men",
        "entity_keys": [
          "gni",
          "cdi",
          "col",
          "cook",
          "msh",
          "poli",
          "nsk",
          "hva"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " first put on the dress they had prepared for her out of their trousers, she began to sing and dance. She sang this song:8"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "hi(i)hihiyo'oo (twice)\nkachnaualanalna'al (swinging in the dance when this line was sung)\nhihihiyo'oo"
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "The Indians made blankets, sometimes by using strips of grass woven together. They called this grass grama in Spanish; it has long roots. As late as — [they still made them?]; "
      },
      {
        "text": "Fernando",
        "entity_key": "fki",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " still — — of this stuff and the sandal from "
      },
      {
        "text": "the San Nicolas woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ".9 She made her skirt of trousers and put a man's shirt on herself. After that [she, they?] threw away her Indian clothes. "
      },
      {
        "text": "The woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " would go to get water at low tide and this was her drinking water."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "HUDSON, TRAVIS",
        "entity_key": "thu",
        "entity_type": "person"
      }
    ],
